{"title_page": "Muncie Flyers", "text_new": "{{see also|Muncie Flyers (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox Pre-modern NFL team\n| name = Muncie Flyers\n| bgcolor = #C41E3A\n| fontcolor = white\n| helmet = \n| logo = \n| founded = 1905\n| suspended = \n| folded = {{Start date and age|1925}}\n| relocated =\n| location = [[Muncie, Indiana]] , [[United States]]\n| field = \n| league = [[National Football League]] (1920)\n| division = \n| colors = Red, White \n{{color box|#C41E3A}} {{color box|white}}\n| history = Congerville Athletic Club (1905\u20131916)<br>Congerville Thirds (1916)<br>Congerville Flyers (1916\u20131920)<br>'''Muncie Flyers (1920\u20131921)'''<br>Congerville Flyers (1922\u20131924)<br />Jonesboro Flyers (1925)\n| nickname = \n| coach = [[Ken Huffine]] (1920) <br> [[Cooney Checkaye]] (1921)\n| manager = \n| owner = Congerville Athletic Club (1905\u201316) <br> [[Earl Ball]] (1917\u20131921) <br> [[Cooney Checkaye]] (1919\u201325)\n| championships = \n| mascot = \n| website =\n}}\n[[File:Congerville flyers 1915.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Congerville Flyers, 1915.]]\n\nThe '''Muncie Flyers''', known as the '''Congerville Flyers''' for most of their existence, were a [[professional football (gridiron)|professional]] [[American football]] team from [[Muncie, Indiana]], that played from 1905 to 1926. The Flyers were an independent squad for most of their existence, but are remembered mostly for their very brief stint in the American Professional Football Association (later known as the [[National Football League]]). With only three official league games, one in 1920 and two in 1921, the Flyers are the third-shortest-lived team in league history, behind the two games of the [[New York Brickley Giants|original New York Giants]] and the one game of the [[Tonawanda Kardex Lumbermen]], and the shortest by a team not from the state of [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nThe origins of the team show that it evolved from the Congerville (Muncie) Athletic Club, which dates back to at least 1905.<ref name=\"sye2002-1\">[[#Sye2002|Sye]] (2002), p. 1</ref> Local newspapers provided spotty coverage of the team. An occasional reference was made to a game being scheduled and sometimes the game results with a brief game account were in the Monday paper. In 1910, the Congerville Athletic Club finished with a 10\u20130\u20131 record, outscoring their opponents 145 to 0.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.profootballarchives.com/1910munca.html | title=1910 Muncie Congerville A.C. | work=The Pro Football Archives | publisher=Maher Sports Media | accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> All of the home games were played against other local Muncie teams, while the road games were played in nearby [[Hartford City, Indiana|Hartford City]], [[Dunkirk, Indiana|Dunkirk]], and [[Alexandria, Indiana|Alexandria]]. In 1916, the Congerville Athletic Club team and the Congerville Flyers team merged and Muncie was represented by the Congerville Flyers.\n\n===The Flyers===\nThe Congerville Muncie Flyers evolved from a team called the '''Congerville Thirds'''. This team was later renamed the Congerville Flyers. The 1915 edition of the Flyers proved to be a respectable team, finishing with a 5\u20133\u20133 record. Their star player was local player Cooney Checkeye. Playing all its games on the road, the 1916 Flyers had a disappointing year, finishing with a 2\u20136\u20131 record. Also representing Congerville in 1915 and 1916 was the [[Congerville Eagles]]. This lightweight team was closely associated with the Flyers, sometimes lending the heavyweight team a player or two when they were short due to injuries.\n\n===World War I===\nThe Congerville Flyers played briefly in 1917, but they did not field a team in 1918 due to the United States involvement in [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu|influenza epidemic]]. In September 1917, [[Earl Ball]] announced that he had organized a team. Scheduled to be on this team were famous college players: [[Dick Abrel]] of [[Purdue University|Purdue]] and [[Al Feeney]] of [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]]. Also scheduled to play was [[Christian Chambers]], formerly of the [[Fort Wayne Friars]]. The team was to be led by local hero [[Cooney Checkaye]]. Ball invited ten more players to come to practice the next morning. However, a week later, on September 9, Ball announced that he had released all the players he had signed and that he would not be fielding a team due to the war. The local press was convinced that had Muncie fielded this team, it would have no doubt been strong contenders for the state championship.\n\n===The NFL era===\nWith the war ended, football came back to life in eastern Indiana. The Flyers played some strong teams, including the [[Wabash Athletic Association]], [[Fort Wayne War Vets]], and Cincinnati Celts. The 1919 team finished with a 4\u20131\u20131 record. In [[1920 NFL season|1920]], the Flyers were one of the original 14 teams in the [[American Professional Football Association]], which later became the National Football League. In the second ever NFL game, the [[Rock Island Independents]] destroyed the Muncie Flyers 45\u20130. The following week, the [[Decatur Staleys]] canceled their game with the Flyers. Muncie found it difficult to schedule another game. While the team was idle, most of its players signed to play with other local teams. The Flyers did have a game scheduled against the [[Dayton Triangles]] on November 7, 1920, but that game was rained out. The Flyers came back in late November and early December and won three non-APFA games, finishing with a 3\u20131\u20130 overall (0\u20131\u20130 APFA) record. Returning to the APFA in [[1921 NFL season|1921]], the Flyers opened the season by crushing the non-APFA [[Elwood Legion]], then lost league games against the [[Evansville Crimson Giants]], and, at home, against the [[Cincinnati Celts]]. They were scheduled to play on November 13, 1921, against the [[Green Bay Packers]], but that game was canceled, leaving the Flyers with a 1\u20132\u20130 overall (0\u20132\u20130 APFA) record. The Flyers' mark in APFA football was an unimpressive 0\u20133\u20130. But during 1920 and 1921, the Flyers posted a 4\u20130\u20130 mark against non-APFA teams. Including 1919, the Flyers posted an 8\u20131\u20131 record against non-APFA teams.\n\n===Post-NFL===\nAfter leaving the APFA, the Muncie Flyers reverted to their original name of the Congerville Flyers. Due to weak fan support, the Flyers played almost all their [[Traveling team|games on the road]] from in 1922, 1923, and 1924. The Flyers did play one home game, in 1924, that was against the \"Notre Dame Reserves of Brownson Hall\". The Flyers lost 47\u20130. Some speculate that the team they played was not really reserves from Notre Dame, but the strong [[South Bend Arrows]]. During those three years, the road-bound Flyers finished with a respectable 10\u20138\u20133 record. In 1925, the Flyers could not find a home field in Muncie, so they based their team out of neighboring [[Jonesboro, Indiana|Jonesboro]]. The team was referred to as the '''Jonesboro Flyers''' and played 9 of 11 games in Jonesboro, finishing with a 6\u20132\u20133 record.\n\n==Season-by-season==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !!W !! L !! T !!Finish!!Coach\n|-\n| 1910 || 11 || 0 || 1|| || [[Earl Ball]]\n|-\n| 1911 || 7 || 1 || 2 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1912 || 6 || 3 || 2 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1913 || 8 || 2 || 0 || Indiana State Champs || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1914 || 5 || 3 || 1 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1915 || 8 || 2 || 1 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1916 || 2 || 7 || 1 || || F. W. Smith\n|-\n| 1917 || 2 || 2 || 0 || || Ky Foster, Ralph Dawson, Zach Toliner\n|-\n| 1918 || colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\" | '''''did not play'''''\n|-\n| 1919 || 4 || 1 || 1 || || [[Cooney Checkaye]] \n|-\n| 1920 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 14th APFA ||[[Ken Huffine]]\n|-\n| 1921 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 18th APFA ||Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1922 || 5 || 1 || 3 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1923 || 3 || 4 || 0 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1924 || 3 || 3 || 0 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1925 || 6 || 2 || 3 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1926 || 0 || 1 || 0 || Incomplete || \n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Cite journal | ref=Sye2002 | last=Sye | first=Roy | year=2002 | title=Muncie Flyers \u2013 1920 | url=http://www.profootballresearchers.org/Coffin_Corner/24-03-937.pdf | format=PDF | journal=[[The Coffin Corner]] | publisher=[[Professional Football Researchers Association]] | volume=24 | issue=3 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511105256/http://www.profootballresearchers.org/Coffin_Corner/24-03-937.pdf | archivedate=2012-05-11 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.independentfootball.site90.com/MuncieFlyers.htm History of the Muncie Flyers Football team]\n\n{{Muncie Flyers seasons}}\n{{NFL charter member}}\n{{Defunct NFL teams}}\n\n[[Category:American football teams established in 1905]]\n[[Category:American football teams disestablished in 1925]]\n[[Category:Defunct National Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct American football teams in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Sports in Muncie, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:1925 disestablishments in Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|Muncie Flyers (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox Pre-modern NFL team\n| name = Muncie Flyers\n| bgcolor = #C41E3A\n| fontcolor = white\n| helmet = \n| logo = \n| founded = 1905\n| suspended = \n| folded = {{Start date and age|1925}}\n| relocated =\n| location = [[Muncie, Indiana]] , [[United States]]\n| field = \n| league = [[National Football League]] (1920)\n| division = \n| colors = Red, White \n{{color box|#C41E3A}} {{color box|white}}\n| history = Congerville Athletic Club (1905\u20131916)<br>Congerville Thirds (1916)<br>Congerville Flyers (1916\u20131920)<br>'''Muncie Flyers (1920\u20131921)'''<br>Congerville Flyers (1922\u20131924)<br />Jonesboro Flyers (1925)\n| nickname = \n| coach = [[Ken Huffine]] (1920) <br> [[Cooney Checkaye]] (1921)\n| manager = \n| owner = Congerville Athletic Club (1905\u201316) <br> [[Earl Ball]] (1917\u20131921) <br> [[Cooney Checkaye]] (1919\u201325)\n| championships = \n| mascot = \n| website =\n}}\n[[File:Congerville flyers 1915.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Congerville Flyers, 1915.]]\n\nThe '''Muncie Flyers''', known as the '''Congerville Flyers''' for most of their existence, were a [[professional football (gridiron)|professional]] [[American football]] team from [[Muncie, Indiana]], that played from 1905 to 1926. The Flyers were an independent squad for most of their existence, but are remembered mostly for their very brief stint in the American Professional Football Association (later known as the [[National Football League]]). With only three official league games, one in 1920 and two in 1921, the Flyers are the third-shortest-lived team in league history, behind the two games of the [[New York Brickley Giants|original New York Giants]] and the one game of the [[Tonawanda Kardex Lumbermen]], and the shortest by a team not from the state of [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nThe origins of the team show that it evolved from the Congerville (Muncie) Athletic Club, which dates back to at least 1905.<ref name=\"sye2002-1\">[[#Sye2002|Sye]] (2002), p. 1</ref> Local newspapers provided spotty coverage of the team. An occasional reference was made to a game being scheduled and sometimes the game results with a brief game account were in the Monday paper. In 1910, the Congerville Athletic Club finished with a 10\u20130\u20131 record, outscoring their opponents 145 to 0.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.profootballarchives.com/1910munca.html | title=1910 Muncie Congerville A.C. | work=The Pro Football Archives | publisher=Maher Sports Media | accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> All of the home games were played against other local Muncie teams, while the road games were played in nearby [[Hartford City, Indiana|Hartford City]], [[Dunkirk, Indiana|Dunkirk]], and [[Alexandria, Indiana|Alexandria]]. In 1916, the Congerville Athletic Club team and the Congerville Flyers team merged and Muncie was represented by the Congerville Flyers.\n\n===The Flyers===\nThe Congerville Muncie Flyers evolved from a team called the '''Congerville Thirds'''. This team was later renamed the Congerville Flyers. The 1915 edition of the Flyers proved to be a respectable team, finishing with a 5\u20133\u20133 record. Their star player was local player Cooney Checkeye. Playing all its games on the road, the 1916 Flyers had a disappointing year, finishing with a 2\u20136\u20131 record. Also representing Congerville in 1915 and 1916 was the [[Congerville Eagles]]. This lightweight team was closely associated with the Flyers, sometimes lending the heavyweight team a player or two when they were short due to injuries.\n\n===World War I===\nThe Congerville Flyers played briefly in 1917, but they did not field a team in 1918 due to the United States involvement in [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu|influenza epidemic]]. In September 1917, [[Earl Ball]] announced that he had organized a team. Scheduled to be on this team were famous college players: [[Dick Abrel]] of [[Purdue University|Purdue]] and [[Al Feeney]] of [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]]. Also scheduled to play was [[Christian Chambers]], formerly of the [[Fort Wayne Friars]]. The team was to be led by local hero [[Cooney Checkaye]]. Ball invited ten more players to come to practice the next morning. However, a week later, on September 9, Ball announced that he had released all the players he had signed and that he would not be fielding a team due to the war. The local press was convinced that had Muncie fielded this team, it would have no doubt been strong contenders for the state championship.\n\n===The NFL era===\nWith the war ended, football came back to life in eastern Indiana. The Flyers played some strong teams, including the [[Wabash Athletic Association]], [[Fort Wayne War Vets]], and Cincinnati Celts. The 1919 team finished with a 4\u20131\u20131 record. In [[1920 NFL season|1920]], the Flyers were one of the original 14 teams in the [[American Professional Football Association]], which later became the National Football League. In the second ever NFL game, the [[Rock Island Independents]] destroyed the Muncie Flyers 45\u20130. The following week, the [[Decatur Staleys]] canceled their game with the Flyers. Muncie found it difficult to schedule another game. While the team was idle, most of its players signed to play with other local teams. The Flyers did have a game scheduled against the [[Dayton Triangles]] on November 7, 1920, but that game was rained out. The Flyers came back in late November and early December and won three non-APFA games, finishing with a 3\u20131\u20130 overall (0\u20131\u20130 APFA) record. Returning to the APFA in [[1921 NFL season|1921]], the Flyers opened the season by crushing the non-APFA [[Elwood Legion]], then lost league games against the [[Evansville Crimson Giants]], and, at home, against the [[Cincinnati Celts]]. They were scheduled to play on November 13, 1921, against the [[Green Bay Packers]], but that game was canceled, leaving the Flyers with a 1\u20132\u20130 overall (0\u20132\u20130 APFA) record. The Flyers' mark in APFA football was an unimpressive 0\u20133\u20130. But during 1920 and 1921, the Flyers posted a 4\u20130\u20130 mark against non-APFA teams. Including 1919, the Flyers posted an 8\u20131\u20131 record against non-APFA teams.\n\n===Post-NFL===\nAfter leaving the APFA, the Muncie Flyers reverted to their original name of the Congerville Flyers. Due to weak fan support, the Flyers played almost all their [[Traveling team|games on the road]] from in 1922, 1923, and 1924. The Flyers did play one home game, in 1924, that was against the \"Notre Dame Reserves of Brownson Hall\". The Flyers lost 47\u20130. Some speculate that the team they played was not really reserves from Notre Dame, but the strong [[South Bend Arrows]]. During those three years, the road-bound Flyers finished with a respectable 10\u20138\u20133 record. In 1925, the Flyers could not find a home field in Muncie, so they based their team out of neighboring [[Jonesboro, Indiana|Jonesboro]]. The team was referred to as the '''Jonesboro Flyers''' and played 9 of 11 games in Jonesboro, finishing with a 6\u20132\u20133 record.\n\n==Season-by-season==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !!W !! L !! T !!Finish!!Coach\n|-\n| 1910 || 11 || 0 || 1|| || [[Earl Ball]]\n|-\n| 1911 || 7 || 1 || 2 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1912 || 6 || 3 || 2 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1913 || 8 || 2 || 0 || Indiana State Champs || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1914 || 5 || 3 || 1 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1915 || 8 || 2 || 1 || || Earl Ball\n|-\n| 1916 || 2 || 7 || 1 || || F. W. Smith\n|-\n| 1917 || 2 || 2 || 0 || || Ky Foster, Ralph Dawson, Zach Toliner\n|-\n| 1918 || colspan=\"5\" align=\"center\" | '''''did not play'''''\n|-\n| 1919 || 4 || 1 || 1 || || [[Cooney Checkaye]] \n|-\n| 1920 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 14th APFA ||[[Ken Huffine]]\n|-\n| 1921 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 18th APFA ||Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1922 || 5 || 1 || 3 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1923 || 3 || 4 || 0 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1924 || 3 || 3 || 0 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1925 || 6 || 2 || 3 || || Cooney Checkaye\n|-\n| 1926 || 0 || 1 || 0 || Incomplete || \n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Cite journal | ref=Sye2002 | last=Sye | first=Roy | year=2002 | title=Muncie Flyers \u2013 1920 | url=http://www.profootballresearchers.org/Coffin_Corner/24-03-937.pdf | format=PDF | journal=[[The Coffin Corner]] | publisher=[[Professional Football Researchers Association]] | volume=24 | issue=3 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511105256/http://www.profootballresearchers.org/Coffin_Corner/24-03-937.pdf | archivedate=2012-05-11 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.independentfootball.site90.com/MuncieFlyers.htm History of the Muncie Flyers Football team]\n\n{{Muncie Flyers seasons}}\n{{NFL charter member}}\n{{Defunct NFL teams}}\n\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1905]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 1925]]\n[[Category:Defunct National Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct American football teams in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Sports in Muncie, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:1925 disestablishments in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muncie_Flyers"}
{"title_page": "The Punisher (1993 video game)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox video game\n | title = The Punisher\n | image = Punisher game flyer.png\n | caption = North American arcade flyer\n | developer = [[Capcom]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9156 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131012020915/http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9156 |archivedate=12 October 2013 |title=The Punisher |work=The International Arcade Museum |accessdate =17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | publisher = Capcom\n | director = [[Noritaka Funamizu]]\n | designer = [[Akira Yasuda]] <br> Jun Keiba <br> Junichi Ohno\n | programmer = Kazuhito Nakai <br> Tomohiro Ueno <br> Yoji Mikami\n | artist = Haruki Suetsugu <br> Eri Nakamura <br> Hiroaki Minobe\n | composer = [[Yoko Shimomura]]<br>Isao Abe\n | released = '''Arcade'''<br>15 March 1993<br>'''Sega Genesis'''<br>{{vgrelease|NA|December 1994|EU|April 1995}}\n | genre = [[Beat 'em up]]\n | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Cooperative gameplay|co-op]]\n | cabinet = Upright\n | arcade system = [[CP System]]\n | sound = [[QSound]]\n | display = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 384 x 224 pixels (horizontal), 4096 colors\n | platform = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Sega Genesis]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''The Punisher'''''|\u30d1\u30cb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e3\u30fc|Panissh\u0101|lead=yes}} is a 1993 [[beat 'em up]] [[arcade game]] developed and released by [[Capcom]]. It stars the [[Marvel Comics]]' [[antihero]] the [[Punisher]] (Frank Castle) and co-stars [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] agent [[Nick Fury]] as the second player's character as they embark on a mission to kill the crime lord the [[Kingpin (character)|Kingpin]] and bring down his organization. While following the same general formula as Capcom's previous beat 'em ups, the game has a range of usable weapons and a comics-style presentation.\n\n''The Punisher'' gained significant popularity in arcades and is widely regarded as one of the best titles in the beat 'em up genre as well as one of the best video game adaptations of comic books. A [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive/Genesis]] port was developed by [[Sculptured Software]] and published by Capcom to mixed reviews and commercial failure.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Punisher arcade gameplay.png|thumb|left|[[cooperative gameplay|Co-op gameplay]] in Stage 3 \"Waterfront Warfare\" of the arcade version, with the [[Punisher]] and [[Nick Fury]] facing the [[Pretty Boy (comics)|Pretty Boys]] and ninja women|alt=|300x300px]]\n\n''The Punisher'' follows the same [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[beat'em up]] formula [[Capcom]] established in ''[[Final Fight (video game)|Final Fight]]'' and ''[[Captain Commando]]''<ref name=gamepower/> as the protagonists engage ordinary foes and [[Boss (video gaming)|stage bosses]]. As in most beat'em up games of this kind, progression through the game is achieved by systematically dispatching all common enemies and proceeding to the right (or left), and defeating the bosses met at the end of each [[Level (video gaming)|stage]]. Unlike in ''Final Fight'', the size, abilities and tactics of both [[player character]]s (the [[Punisher]] and [[Nick Fury]]) are essentially interchangeable; they both use the same basic moves, such as punches, kicks and throws, which can be chained into [[Combo (video gaming)|combo]]s, as well as similar special attacks.<ref name=if/><ref name=vgc/> Basic attacks can be combined to cause extra damage to enemies.<ref name=allgame/> The game is presented in a comic book-like style, including featuring on-screen onomatopoeias such as \"BLAM!\" for gunshots.<ref name=gamestalker>{{cite web |last=Damen |first=Pepijn |url=http://www.gamestalker.nl/klapper-woensdag-the-punisher/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130927134915/http://www.gamestalker.nl/klapper-woensdag-the-punisher/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |title=Klapper Woensdag The Punisher |work=Gamestalker |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nVarious melee (including baseball bats and Japanese swords) and thrown weapons (including knives and [[shuriken]])<ref name=allgame/> as well as improvised weapons (such as lead pipes, car tires<ref name=gamestalker/> and a crude flamethrower<ref name=heavy/>) can be picked up during regular combat. Weapons can be dropped by killed enemies or obtained from smashing various containers throughout the stages. When the player is armed with a weapon, its durability will be displayed alongside the player's health, showing how much it can be used until it breaks apart. Treasure can also be found in containers, awarding the player with bonus [[Score (game)|score points]] once collected (jewelry also appears after defeating female enemies). Health can be replenished by picking up food, which can also give bonus points.<ref name=allgame/> The game distinguished itself by the relatively high level of violence in a video game of the era,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 1993|title=Quarter Crunchers: The Punisher|url=|journal=GameFan|volume=1-08|pages=90|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> as well by the frequent use of firearms,<ref name=if/><ref name=nerd/> including an [[Ingram MAC-10|Ingram]] and a [[M16 rifle|M16]].<ref name=heavy/> There are several sections of the game when gun-wielding enemies appear to which the characters draw their handguns, enabling the player to shoot them. Player characters can also pick up and collect hand grenades that can be deployed at a moment of choice.<ref name=vgc/><ref name=allgame/>\n\n==Plot==\nIn the games intro, U.S. Marine Captain Frank Castle enjoys a picnic with his family in Central Park. The Castle family accidentally discovered a mob killing. Fearing any witnesses, the killers gunned down the family. To avenge them and all others like them Frank becomes The Punisher. The game begins in an illegal casino and the streets of the [[New York City]], with the merciless [[vigilante]] Frank \"the Punisher\" Castle (optionally partnered with [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] agent Nick Fury) in pursuit of the [[Italian-American Mafia|Mafia]] enforcer Bruno Costa who ordered the killing of Castle's family; the chase ends with a fight against Chester Scully (a minor villain from the comics). Frank \"interrogates\" Scully, gets the information he needs, and then promptly shoots him. Still on track of Bruno, the Punisher infiltrates the mob's Pantaberde resort in Florida via a water duct. He breaks into a hotel and corners Bruno, who is suddenly killed by a robot called Guardroid, who tells Frank the Kingpin has programmed him to terminate him, which the Punisher must then take on.\n\nThe Punisher then raids a major drug-smuggling ring at the local harbor, which ends with him confronting [[Bonebreaker]] in a waterfront warehouse. After that, the Punisher attacks the [[Kingpin (comics)|Kingpin]]'s poppy field at a cave in [[Arizona]]. The Punisher boards and destroys a freight train which is commanded by [[Bushwacker (comics)|Bushwhacker]].\n\nAt that point, the Kingpin decides that he has lost enough henchmen and money to the Punisher's actions. He puts a hefty contract out on him, and he is chased by assassins from his hideout and through a forest. After defeating another Guardroid, the Punisher in turn assaults the King Building skyscraper. He fights his way through [[Jigsaw (Marvel Comics)|Jigsaw]] and other enemies to the final showdown against the Kingpin himself. After the Kingpin is defeated, the entire tower collapses, but the Kingpin is not found among the many dead criminals in the rubble.\n\n==Development and release==\n===Arcade===\n''The Punisher'' for the arcades was released in April 1993,<ref name=gamestalker/> marking the beginning of the partnership between [[Marvel Comics]] and Capcom, which led to the series ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom (series)|Marvel vs. Capcom]]''.<ref name=\"MvC:OCW\">{{cite book|title=Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works|author=UDON Entertainment|year=2012|publisher=Diamond Comics|location=Hong Kong|isbn=9781926778495|page=2}}</ref> The game used a new arcade system, allowing over 10 enemies to appear on screen at the same time without slowdowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> A pre-release version included some cut content such as rocket launchers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1993|title=The Punisher|url=|journal=Electronic Gaming Monthly|volume=46|pages=58|via=}}</ref> Artworks from the game were featured in the 2012 art book ''Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works'' by [[Udon Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udonentertainment.com/blog/udon/2012-in-review-marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306135025/http://www.udonentertainment.com/blog/news/2012-in-review-marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Blog Archive \u00bb Marvel vs. Capcom Official Complete Works (UDON 2012 in Review) |work=[[Udon Entertainment]] |date=14 January 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> In 2019, the game was announced to one of the titles to be includes in the Marvel Arcade1Up arcade cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/games/classic-marvel-arcade-cabinets-announced-at-e3-2019|title=Classic Marvel Arcade Cabinets Announced at E3 2019 {{!}} News {{!}} Marvel|website=Marvel Entertainment|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref>\n\n===Genesis===\nA console port of ''The Punisher'' was released for the [[Sega Genesis|Genesis]] in North America in 1994 and for the [[PAL region]] Mega Drive in April 1995.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://archive.org/stream/HobbyConsolas043/Hobby_Consolas_043#page/n55/mode/2up |title=The Punisher |date=April 1995 |work=[[Hobby Consolas]] |issue=43 |pages=56\u201357}}</ref> This version, while published by Capcom, was developed by an independent American company [[Sculptured Software]].<ref name=rank/> In addition to the worse graphics and sound, lesser variety of enemies, and a smaller number of objects on screen than in the original, many of the previously breakable background objects were rendered unbreakable due to the limitations of the Genesis' hardware.<ref name=gamestalker/>\n\nThis version also contains some [[video game censorship|content censorship]], including removing the most explicit violence as well as the animation of Fury smoking his cigar,<ref name=if/> and female ninja enemies with skimpy outfits becoming fully clothed.<ref name=gamestalker/> The port also comes with three difficulty settings,<ref name=vgc>''Video Games & Computer Entertainment'' issue 80 (September 1995), page 26.</ref> but the Easy setting ends after only three stages and the game can be properly completed only on Normal or Hard. The [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] version was reported in works by [[Crystal Dynamics]], but was never completed.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_086_September_1996/page/n21 |title=Dynamic Changes at Crystal Dynamics |magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=86 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=September 1996 |page=21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n | GR = 73% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=rank>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586402-the-punisher/index.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130123180817/http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586402-the-punisher/index.html |archivedate=23 January 2013 |title=The Punisher for Genesis |work=GameRankings |date= |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | Allgame = {{Rating|2.5|5}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=allgame>{{cite web|last=Cook |first=Brad |url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=7584 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115000851/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=7584 |archivedate=15 November 2014 |title=The Punisher Overview |work=[[AllGame]] |date=3 October 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | EGM = {{Rating|6|10}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=\"EGM68\"/>\n | Hyper = 48% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=hyper>''Hyper'' issue 150, page 79.</ref>\n | NGen = {{Rating|1|5}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=ng/>\n | rev1 = ''GamePower''\n | rev1Score = 33/40 <small>(Arcade)</small><ref name=gamepower>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |date=August 1993 |title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePower_Ano_2_No._14_1993-08_Nova_Cultural_BR_pt#page/n33/mode/2up |magazine=GamePower |issue=14 |page=35}}</ref><br>3.8/5 <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>\n{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |date=June 1995|title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/stream/SuperGamePower_Ano_02_No._015_1995-06_Nova_Cultural_BR_pt#page/n31/mode |magazine=SuperGamePower |issue=15 |page=32}}</ref>\n | rev2 = ''[[Hobby Consolas]]''\n | rev2Score = 81% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/HobbyConsolas044/Hobby_Consolas_044#page/n69/mode/2up |title=The Punisher |work=[[Hobby Consolas]] |issue=44 |pages=70\u201371}}</ref>\n | rev3 = ''Man!ac''\n | rev3Score = 58% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=German |title=The Punisher |magazine=Man!ac |date=July 1995 |page=69}}</ref>\n | rev4 = ''Player One''\n | rev4Score = 60% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=French |date=July\u2013August 1995 |title=Le Zoom de Vite Vu |magazine=Player One |volume=55 |page=114}}</ref>\n | rev5 = ''Superjuegos''\n | rev5Score = 68% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |title=Un verdadero castigo |magazine=Superjuegos |volume=37 |pages=112\u2013113}}</ref>\n | rev6 = ''TodoSega''\n | rev6Score = 84% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=ts>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |title=The Punisher |magazine=TodoSega |volume=26 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref>\n | rev7 = ''Top Consoles''\n | rev7Score = 13% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{Cite magazine |language=French |date=July\u2013August 1995 |title=The Punisher |magazine=Top Consoles |volume=4 |pages=98\u2013101}}</ref>\n | rev8 = ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment|VG&CE]]''\n | rev8Score = 7/10 <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=vg/>\n}}\n\n===Arcade===\nUpon its release, ''GamePower'' gave the arcade version of ''The Punisher'' a perfect partial score for the game's \"fun factor\".<ref name=gamepower/> Its action was praised by ''[[GamePro]]'', who remarked that \"this game's outstanding feature is its gorgeous graphics, which capture the dark, somber mood of the [[List of The Punisher titles|''Punisher'' comic books]].\"<ref>''GamePro'' issue 49 (August 1993), page 20.</ref> ''[[GameFan]]'' reviewer wrote ''The Punisher'' \"proved to be everything I dreamed of in a traditional ''Final Fight''-style game,\"<ref name=\":0\" /> having previously described it as \"definitely the greatest side scrolling fighting game ever\" as well as \"the bloodiest, goriest fighting game since ''[[Mortal Kombat (1992 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]''\" in his preview.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Genesis===\nReviewing the Genesis conversion, ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment|VideoGames]]'' called it \"a decent exercise in vigilante mayhem\" that is \"surprisingly fun, yet fairly standard game.\"<ref name=vg>{{cite magazine |date=June 1995 |magazine=VideoGames - The Ultimate Gaming Magazine |title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/details/Video_Games_The_Ultimate_Gaming_Magazine_Issue_77_June_1995 |issue=77 |page=84 }}</ref> A preview by ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]'' opined it \"looks good\" and features \"fantastic weaponry\",<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/mean-machines-sega-magazine-24/MMSega_24_Oct_1994#page/n11/mode/2up |title=Punish Me Gently |date=April 1995 |work=[[Mean Machines Sega]] |issue=24 |page=12}}</ref> but ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' criticized the characters for being too small on the screen, also stating that there was little to no skill involved in defeating the bosses. ''EGM'' praised the number of weapons and moves available but nonetheless concluded that \"the whole game comes across as routine and bland.\"<ref name=\"EGM68\">{{cite magazine |last= |first= |title=Review Crew: The Punisher |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=68 |publisher=EGM Media |date=March 1995 |page=36}}</ref> ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega Play]]'' reviewers especially criticized the port's removal of gore and the \"drab\" and \"dull\" color palette, issuing it four scores of between 67-72%.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=|title=Mega Reviews!!|url=|magazine=Mega Play|volume=6|issue=3|pages=47|via=}}</ref>\n\n''GamePro'' outright panned the port, commenting that the special moves are too difficult to pull off, the sound effects are weak, the gameplay is generic and unimaginative beat 'em up fare, and \"the graphics never come close to the [[coin-op]] game that this cart is based on.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_069_April_1995/page/n47 |title=ProReview: The Punisher |magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=69 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=April 1995 |page=47}}</ref> It was also lambasted by ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', who stated that \"not much good can be found\" in the game and \"the person responsible for putting out ''The Punisher'' deserves a good spanking.\"<ref name=ng>{{cite magazine |date=July 1995 |title=Execution |url=https://archive.org/stream/nextgen-issue-007/Next_Generation_Issue_007_July_1995#page/n79/mode/2up |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=7 |page=77}}</ref> ''[[Hyper (magazine)|Hyper]]'' even had ''The Punisher'' as the worst rated game of the month, describing it as \"almost like an [[8-bit|8 bit]] game: scrappy graphics, stilted animation, sloooowww [[scrolling]] and only two (yes, two) buttons on the controller used.\"<ref name=hyper/> The game sold poorly, resulting in it becoming one the rarest [[PAL]] region titles for the platform.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=|title=Mega Drive: The Collector's Guide|url=|magazine=Retro Gamer|volume=112|pages=76|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective===\nNotwithstanding the flawed home port and limited commercial success, the arcade original has achieved a cult game status. ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]'' and ''[[Official U.S. PlayStation Magazine]]'' both wished for ''The Punisher'' to be included in Capcom's arcade compilation releases for the [[Sega Saturn]] and the PlayStation, respectively.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_034/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_034_-_august_1998_UK#page/n41/mode/2up/search/punisher|title=Capcom Generation Vol 4 |magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |date=August 1998 |issue=34 |page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Sega_Saturn_Magazine_Issue_31_1998-05_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n31/mode/2up|title=Capcom Generation |magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |date=May 1998 |issue=31 |page=33}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_US_PlayStation_Magazine_Volume_2_Issue_8_1999-05_Ziff_Davis_US#page/n77/mode/2up/search/punisher |title=In the Year 2000 |magazine=[[Official U.S. PlayStation Magazine]] |date=May 1999 |volume=2 |issue=8 |page=78}}</ref> According to ''[[GamesTM]]'' in 2005, \"Capcom's ''The Punisher'' was a brutally violent fighter that perfectly captured the [[antihero]] it was based on. Featuring buckets of blood, some nasty moves and hordes of enemies, action came thick and fast, and so did the excitement.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/gamesTM023/GTM_023_eMag#page/n127/mode/2up/|title=It Started With a Fist |magazine=[[GamesTM]] |issue=23 |page=136}}</ref> The magazine too expressed a wish for it to be included in a compilation re-release for a more modern gaming system, in this case the [[PlayStation Portable]], but noted that the chances of this are slim due to a long-expired license.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/gamesTM044/GTM_044_eMag#page/n137/mode/2up/ |title=Compilation Heaven |magazine=[[GamesTM]] |issue=44 |page=138}}</ref>\n\n''[[Retro Gamer]]'' called it \"a forgotten gem in Capcom's back catalogue\" that \"is bursting with character and is extremely enjoyable,\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=McFerran |first=Damien |title=The Making Of... Dungeons & Dragons - Best Brawlers: Punisher (1993)\" |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=72 |p=52 |date=2010 |issn=1742-3155}}</ref> surmising the game did not sell well because the market was already flooded with beat 'em up games.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Buchanan |first=Adam |title=The Collector's Guide: Sega Mega Drive - Top Rarest PAL Games: The Punisher |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=112 |p=76 |date=2013 |issn=1742-3155}}</ref> Some media outlets also singled out for a special praise the game's particular elements, such as with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' regarding its arcade cabinet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/06/all-hail-the-90s-10-marvel-cabinets-that-ruled-the-arcades/the-punisher |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072809/http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/06/all-hail-the-90s-10-marvel-cabinets-that-ruled-the-arcades/the-punisher |archivedate=4 March 2016|title=The Punisher - All Hail the '90s: 10 Marvel Cabinets That Ruled the Arcades - Complex|author=Rich Knight|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> and [[Cracked.com]] regarding its [[game over]] sequence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_21313_the-5-most-sadistic-game-over-scenes-in-video-game-history.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150508211630/http://www.cracked.com/article_21313_the-5-most-sadistic-game-over-scenes-in-video-game-history.html|archivedate=8 May 2015|title=The 5 Most Sadistic 'Game Over' Scenes in Video Game History|work=[[Cracked.com]]|accessdate=23 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Crunchyroll]]'s [[Patrick Macias]] wrote: \"I'll confess my heart skipped a beat when I read ''The Punisher'' arcade game, the legacy of a misspent youth and countless tokens whittled away at [[Chuck E. Cheese's|Chuck E. Cheese]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/07/10/marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works-book-to-debut-at-san-diego-comic-con |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130120011727/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/07/10/marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works-book-to-debut-at-san-diego-comic-con |archivedate=20 January 2013 |title=\"Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works\" Book to Debut at San Diego Comic-Con |work=[[Crunchyroll]] |date=11 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Patrick Macias |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSome critics regard ''The Punisher'' as among the best of the beat 'em up genre, as well as among the best video game adaptations of comic books, especially of Marvel titles. In 2010, it was ranked as the tenth top greatest [[superhero]] game by [[IGN]]'s News & Features Team,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://ign.com/articles/2007/05/16/top-10-tuesdays-greatest-superhero-games |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170222120603/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/05/16/top-10-tuesdays-greatest-superhero-games |archivedate=22 February 2017 |title=Top 10 Tuesdays: Greatest Superhero Games |work=[[IGN]] |date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=News & Features Team |url-status=dead }}</ref> and as the fifth top Marvel arcade game by [[iFanboy]]'s Josh Richardson.<ref name=if>{{cite web|url=http://ifanboy.com/articles/top-five-marvel-arcade-games/ |title=Top Five Marvel Arcade Games |work=[[IFanboy]] |date=6 March 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014|first=Josh |last=Richardson}}</ref> [[Nerdist Industries]] included it among the top ten most iconic Marvel video games in 2013, calling it \"one of the few games that benefits from its cheesiness\" and stating that in 1993 the two-player experience \"was pretty much what ''[[Army of Two]]'' wishes it was today.\"<ref name=nerd>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/top-ten-most-iconic-marvel-video-games/comment-page-1/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193128/http://nerdist.com/top-ten-most-iconic-marvel-video-games/comment-page-1/ |archivedate=4 March 2016 |title=Top Ten Most Iconic Marvel Video Games \u00ab Nerdist |work=[[Nerdist Industries]] |date=8 November 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> That same year, it was also listed as one of top beat 'em up games of all time by [[Heavy.com]]'s Elton Jones,<ref name=heavy>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/games/2013/05/the-top-25-beat-em-up-video-games-part-2/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140917081157/http://heavy.com/games/2013/05/the-top-25-beat-em-up-video-games-part-2/ |archivedate=17 September 2014 |title=The Top 25 Beat 'Em Up Video Games Part 2 |work=[[Heavy.com]] |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as being included amongst the best looking beat 'em up games from the [[16-bit]] era by [[Kotaku]] Australia's Gergo Vas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2013/03/the-best-looking-beat-em-up-games-from-the-16-bit-era/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130616074120/http://www.kotaku.com.au/2013/03/the-best-looking-beat-em-up-games-from-the-16-bit-era/ |archivedate=16 June 2013 |title=The Best Looking Beat em Up Games From The 16-Bit Era &#124; Kotaku Australia |work=[[Kotaku]] |date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Gergo Vas |url-status=dead }}</ref> David Hawkins of WhatCulture! declared it number one best comics-based arcade game in a 2011 ranking, being \"above and beyond all other arcade adaptations of comic books and their heroes,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/the-top-ten-comic-book-arcade-games.php |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131015192046/http://whatculture.com/gaming/the-top-ten-comic-book-arcade-games.php |archivedate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |title=10 Top Comic Book Arcade Games |work=WhatCulture |date=4 September 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=David Hawkins }}</ref> and Jon Ledford of Arcade Sushi opined that \"in terms of pure enjoyment, ingenuity, control, and graphics, ''The Punisher'' is the Best Retro Beat 'Em Up of all time.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arcadesushi.com/best-retro-beat-em-ups/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130927135033/http://arcadesushi.com/best-retro-beat-em-ups/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |title=10 Best Retro Beat Em Ups |work=Arcade Sushi |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Jon Ledford |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External linksf==\n*{{moby game|id=/punisher__|name=''The Punisher''}}\n\n{{Punisher}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Punisher, The}}\n[[Category:1993 video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Capcom beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Censored video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation (console) games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Video games based on Punisher]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Video games set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Yoko Shimomura]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox video game\n | title = The Punisher\n | image = Punisher game flyer.png\n | caption = North American arcade flyer\n | developer = [[Capcom]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9156 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131012020915/http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=9156 |archivedate=12 October 2013 |title=The Punisher |work=The International Arcade Museum |accessdate =17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | publisher = Capcom\n | director = [[Noritaka Funamizu]]\n | designer = [[Akira Yasuda]] <br> Jun Keiba <br> Junichi Ohno\n | programmer = Kazuhito Nakai <br> Tomohiro Ueno <br> Yoji Mikami\n | artist = Haruki Suetsugu <br> Eri Nakamura <br> Hiroaki Minobe\n | composer = [[Yoko Shimomura]]<br>Isao Abe\n | released = '''Arcade'''<br>1993<br>'''Sega Genesis'''<br>{{vgrelease|NA|December 1994|EU|April 1995}}\n | genre = [[Beat 'em up]]\n | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Cooperative gameplay|co-op]]\n | cabinet = Upright\n | arcade system = [[CP System]]\n | sound = [[QSound]]\n | display = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 384 x 224 pixels (horizontal), 4096 colors\n | platform = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Sega Genesis]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''The Punisher'''''|\u30d1\u30cb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e3\u30fc|Panissh\u0101|lead=yes}} is a 1993 [[beat 'em up]] [[arcade game]] developed and released by [[Capcom]]. It stars the [[Marvel Comics]]' [[antihero]] the [[Punisher]] (Frank Castle) and co-stars [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] agent [[Nick Fury]] as the second player's character as they embark on a mission to kill the crime lord the [[Kingpin (character)|Kingpin]] and bring down his organization. While following the same general formula as Capcom's previous beat 'em ups, the game has a range of usable weapons and a comics-style presentation.\n\n''The Punisher'' gained significant popularity in arcades and is widely regarded as one of the best titles in the beat 'em up genre as well as one of the best video game adaptations of comic books. A [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive/Genesis]] port was developed by [[Sculptured Software]] and published by Capcom to mixed reviews and commercial failure.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Punisher arcade gameplay.png|thumb|left|[[cooperative gameplay|Co-op gameplay]] in Stage 3 \"Waterfront Warfare\" of the arcade version, with the [[Punisher]] and [[Nick Fury]] facing the [[Pretty Boy (comics)|Pretty Boys]] and ninja women|alt=|300x300px]]\n\n''The Punisher'' follows the same [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[beat'em up]] formula [[Capcom]] established in ''[[Final Fight (video game)|Final Fight]]'' and ''[[Captain Commando]]''<ref name=gamepower/> as the protagonists engage ordinary foes and [[Boss (video gaming)|stage bosses]]. As in most beat'em up games of this kind, progression through the game is achieved by systematically dispatching all common enemies and proceeding to the right (or left), and defeating the bosses met at the end of each [[Level (video gaming)|stage]]. Unlike in ''Final Fight'', the size, abilities and tactics of both [[player character]]s (the [[Punisher]] and [[Nick Fury]]) are essentially interchangeable; they both use the same basic moves, such as punches, kicks and throws, which can be chained into [[Combo (video gaming)|combo]]s, as well as similar special attacks.<ref name=if/><ref name=vgc/> Basic attacks can be combined to cause extra damage to enemies.<ref name=allgame/> The game is presented in a comic book-like style, including featuring on-screen onomatopoeias such as \"BLAM!\" for gunshots.<ref name=gamestalker>{{cite web |last=Damen |first=Pepijn |url=http://www.gamestalker.nl/klapper-woensdag-the-punisher/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130927134915/http://www.gamestalker.nl/klapper-woensdag-the-punisher/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |title=Klapper Woensdag The Punisher |work=Gamestalker |date=22 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nVarious melee (including baseball bats and Japanese swords) and thrown weapons (including knives and [[shuriken]])<ref name=allgame/> as well as improvised weapons (such as lead pipes, car tires<ref name=gamestalker/> and a crude flamethrower<ref name=heavy/>) can be picked up during regular combat. Weapons can be dropped by killed enemies or obtained from smashing various containers throughout the stages. When the player is armed with a weapon, its durability will be displayed alongside the player's health, showing how much it can be used until it breaks apart. Treasure can also be found in containers, awarding the player with bonus [[Score (game)|score points]] once collected (jewelry also appears after defeating female enemies). Health can be replenished by picking up food, which can also give bonus points.<ref name=allgame/> The game distinguished itself by the relatively high level of violence in a video game of the era,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 1993|title=Quarter Crunchers: The Punisher|url=|journal=GameFan|volume=1-08|pages=90|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> as well by the frequent use of firearms,<ref name=if/><ref name=nerd/> including an [[Ingram MAC-10|Ingram]] and a [[M16 rifle|M16]].<ref name=heavy/> There are several sections of the game when gun-wielding enemies appear to which the characters draw their handguns, enabling the player to shoot them. Player characters can also pick up and collect hand grenades that can be deployed at a moment of choice.<ref name=vgc/><ref name=allgame/>\n\n==Plot==\nIn the games intro, U.S. Marine Captain Frank Castle enjoys a picnic with his family in Central Park. The Castle family accidentally discovered a mob killing. Fearing any witnesses, the killers gunned down the family. To avenge them and all others like them Frank becomes The Punisher. The game begins in an illegal casino and the streets of the [[New York City]], with the merciless [[vigilante]] Frank \"the Punisher\" Castle (optionally partnered with [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] agent Nick Fury) in pursuit of the [[Italian-American Mafia|Mafia]] enforcer Bruno Costa who ordered the killing of Castle's family; the chase ends with a fight against Chester Scully (a minor villain from the comics). Frank \"interrogates\" Scully, gets the information he needs, and then promptly shoots him. Still on track of Bruno, the Punisher infiltrates the mob's Pantaberde resort in Florida via a water duct. He breaks into a hotel and corners Bruno, who is suddenly killed by a robot called Guardroid, who tells Frank the Kingpin has programmed him to terminate him, which the Punisher must then take on.\n\nThe Punisher then raids a major drug-smuggling ring at the local harbor, which ends with him confronting [[Bonebreaker]] in a waterfront warehouse. After that, the Punisher attacks the [[Kingpin (comics)|Kingpin]]'s poppy field at a cave in [[Arizona]]. The Punisher boards and destroys a freight train which is commanded by [[Bushwacker (comics)|Bushwhacker]].\n\nAt that point, the Kingpin decides that he has lost enough henchmen and money to the Punisher's actions. He puts a hefty contract out on him, and he is chased by assassins from his hideout and through a forest. After defeating another Guardroid, the Punisher in turn assaults the King Building skyscraper. He fights his way through [[Jigsaw (Marvel Comics)|Jigsaw]] and other enemies to the final showdown against the Kingpin himself. After the Kingpin is defeated, the entire tower collapses, but the Kingpin is not found among the many dead criminals in the rubble.\n\n==Development and release==\n===Arcade===\n''The Punisher'' for the arcades was released in April 1993,<ref name=gamestalker/> marking the beginning of the partnership between [[Marvel Comics]] and Capcom, which led to the series ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom (series)|Marvel vs. Capcom]]''.<ref name=\"MvC:OCW\">{{cite book|title=Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works|author=UDON Entertainment|year=2012|publisher=Diamond Comics|location=Hong Kong|isbn=9781926778495|page=2}}</ref> The game used a new arcade system, allowing over 10 enemies to appear on screen at the same time without slowdowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> A pre-release version included some cut content such as rocket launchers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1993|title=The Punisher|url=|journal=Electronic Gaming Monthly|volume=46|pages=58|via=}}</ref> Artworks from the game were featured in the 2012 art book ''Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works'' by [[Udon Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udonentertainment.com/blog/udon/2012-in-review-marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306135025/http://www.udonentertainment.com/blog/news/2012-in-review-marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works |archivedate=6 March 2016 |title=Blog Archive \u00bb Marvel vs. Capcom Official Complete Works (UDON 2012 in Review) |work=[[Udon Entertainment]] |date=14 January 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> In 2019, the game was announced to one of the titles to be includes in the Marvel Arcade1Up arcade cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/games/classic-marvel-arcade-cabinets-announced-at-e3-2019|title=Classic Marvel Arcade Cabinets Announced at E3 2019 {{!}} News {{!}} Marvel|website=Marvel Entertainment|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref>\n\n===Genesis===\nA console port of ''The Punisher'' was released for the [[Sega Genesis|Genesis]] in North America in 1994 and for the [[PAL region]] Mega Drive in April 1995.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://archive.org/stream/HobbyConsolas043/Hobby_Consolas_043#page/n55/mode/2up |title=The Punisher |date=April 1995 |work=[[Hobby Consolas]] |issue=43 |pages=56\u201357}}</ref> This version, while published by Capcom, was developed by an independent American company [[Sculptured Software]].<ref name=rank/> In addition to the worse graphics and sound, lesser variety of enemies, and a smaller number of objects on screen than in the original, many of the previously breakable background objects were rendered unbreakable due to the limitations of the Genesis' hardware.<ref name=gamestalker/>\n\nThis version also contains some [[video game censorship|content censorship]], including removing the most explicit violence as well as the animation of Fury smoking his cigar,<ref name=if/> and female ninja enemies with skimpy outfits becoming fully clothed.<ref name=gamestalker/> The port also comes with three difficulty settings,<ref name=vgc>''Video Games & Computer Entertainment'' issue 80 (September 1995), page 26.</ref> but the Easy setting ends after only three stages and the game can be properly completed only on Normal or Hard. The [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] version was reported in works by [[Crystal Dynamics]], but was never completed.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_086_September_1996/page/n21 |title=Dynamic Changes at Crystal Dynamics |magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=86 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=September 1996 |page=21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n | GR = 73% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=rank>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586402-the-punisher/index.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130123180817/http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586402-the-punisher/index.html |archivedate=23 January 2013 |title=The Punisher for Genesis |work=GameRankings |date= |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | Allgame = {{Rating|2.5|5}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=allgame>{{cite web|last=Cook |first=Brad |url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=7584 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115000851/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=7584 |archivedate=15 November 2014 |title=The Punisher Overview |work=[[AllGame]] |date=3 October 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n | EGM = {{Rating|6|10}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=\"EGM68\"/>\n | Hyper = 48% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=hyper>''Hyper'' issue 150, page 79.</ref>\n | NGen = {{Rating|1|5}} <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=ng/>\n | rev1 = ''GamePower''\n | rev1Score = 33/40 <small>(Arcade)</small><ref name=gamepower>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |date=August 1993 |title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/stream/GamePower_Ano_2_No._14_1993-08_Nova_Cultural_BR_pt#page/n33/mode/2up |magazine=GamePower |issue=14 |page=35}}</ref><br>3.8/5 <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>\n{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |date=June 1995|title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/stream/SuperGamePower_Ano_02_No._015_1995-06_Nova_Cultural_BR_pt#page/n31/mode |magazine=SuperGamePower |issue=15 |page=32}}</ref>\n | rev2 = ''[[Hobby Consolas]]''\n | rev2Score = 81% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/HobbyConsolas044/Hobby_Consolas_044#page/n69/mode/2up |title=The Punisher |work=[[Hobby Consolas]] |issue=44 |pages=70\u201371}}</ref>\n | rev3 = ''Man!ac''\n | rev3Score = 58% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=German |title=The Punisher |magazine=Man!ac |date=July 1995 |page=69}}</ref>\n | rev4 = ''Player One''\n | rev4Score = 60% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=French |date=July\u2013August 1995 |title=Le Zoom de Vite Vu |magazine=Player One |volume=55 |page=114}}</ref>\n | rev5 = ''Superjuegos''\n | rev5Score = 68% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |title=Un verdadero castigo |magazine=Superjuegos |volume=37 |pages=112\u2013113}}</ref>\n | rev6 = ''TodoSega''\n | rev6Score = 84% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=ts>{{cite magazine |language=Spanish |title=The Punisher |magazine=TodoSega |volume=26 |pages=36\u201337}}</ref>\n | rev7 = ''Top Consoles''\n | rev7Score = 13% <small>(Genesis)</small><ref>{{Cite magazine |language=French |date=July\u2013August 1995 |title=The Punisher |magazine=Top Consoles |volume=4 |pages=98\u2013101}}</ref>\n | rev8 = ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment|VG&CE]]''\n | rev8Score = 7/10 <small>(Genesis)</small><ref name=vg/>\n}}\n\n===Arcade===\nUpon its release, ''GamePower'' gave the arcade version of ''The Punisher'' a perfect partial score for the game's \"fun factor\".<ref name=gamepower/> Its action was praised by ''[[GamePro]]'', who remarked that \"this game's outstanding feature is its gorgeous graphics, which capture the dark, somber mood of the [[List of The Punisher titles|''Punisher'' comic books]].\"<ref>''GamePro'' issue 49 (August 1993), page 20.</ref> ''[[GameFan]]'' reviewer wrote ''The Punisher'' \"proved to be everything I dreamed of in a traditional ''Final Fight''-style game,\"<ref name=\":0\" /> having previously described it as \"definitely the greatest side scrolling fighting game ever\" as well as \"the bloodiest, goriest fighting game since ''[[Mortal Kombat (1992 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]''\" in his preview.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Genesis===\nReviewing the Genesis conversion, ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment|VideoGames]]'' called it \"a decent exercise in vigilante mayhem\" that is \"surprisingly fun, yet fairly standard game.\"<ref name=vg>{{cite magazine |date=June 1995 |magazine=VideoGames - The Ultimate Gaming Magazine |title=The Punisher |url=https://archive.org/details/Video_Games_The_Ultimate_Gaming_Magazine_Issue_77_June_1995 |issue=77 |page=84 }}</ref> A preview by ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]'' opined it \"looks good\" and features \"fantastic weaponry\",<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/mean-machines-sega-magazine-24/MMSega_24_Oct_1994#page/n11/mode/2up |title=Punish Me Gently |date=April 1995 |work=[[Mean Machines Sega]] |issue=24 |page=12}}</ref> but ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' criticized the characters for being too small on the screen, also stating that there was little to no skill involved in defeating the bosses. ''EGM'' praised the number of weapons and moves available but nonetheless concluded that \"the whole game comes across as routine and bland.\"<ref name=\"EGM68\">{{cite magazine |last= |first= |title=Review Crew: The Punisher |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |issue=68 |publisher=EGM Media |date=March 1995 |page=36}}</ref> ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega Play]]'' reviewers especially criticized the port's removal of gore and the \"drab\" and \"dull\" color palette, issuing it four scores of between 67-72%.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=|title=Mega Reviews!!|url=|magazine=Mega Play|volume=6|issue=3|pages=47|via=}}</ref>\n\n''GamePro'' outright panned the port, commenting that the special moves are too difficult to pull off, the sound effects are weak, the gameplay is generic and unimaginative beat 'em up fare, and \"the graphics never come close to the [[coin-op]] game that this cart is based on.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_069_April_1995/page/n47 |title=ProReview: The Punisher |magazine=[[GamePro]] |issue=69 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=April 1995 |page=47}}</ref> It was also lambasted by ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'', who stated that \"not much good can be found\" in the game and \"the person responsible for putting out ''The Punisher'' deserves a good spanking.\"<ref name=ng>{{cite magazine |date=July 1995 |title=Execution |url=https://archive.org/stream/nextgen-issue-007/Next_Generation_Issue_007_July_1995#page/n79/mode/2up |magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=7 |page=77}}</ref> ''[[Hyper (magazine)|Hyper]]'' even had ''The Punisher'' as the worst rated game of the month, describing it as \"almost like an [[8-bit|8 bit]] game: scrappy graphics, stilted animation, sloooowww [[scrolling]] and only two (yes, two) buttons on the controller used.\"<ref name=hyper/> The game sold poorly, resulting in it becoming one the rarest [[PAL]] region titles for the platform.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=|title=Mega Drive: The Collector's Guide|url=|magazine=Retro Gamer|volume=112|pages=76|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective===\nNotwithstanding the flawed home port and limited commercial success, the arcade original has achieved a cult game status. ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]'' and ''[[Official U.S. PlayStation Magazine]]'' both wished for ''The Punisher'' to be included in Capcom's arcade compilation releases for the [[Sega Saturn]] and the PlayStation, respectively.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_034/Official_Sega_Saturn_Magazine_034_-_august_1998_UK#page/n41/mode/2up/search/punisher|title=Capcom Generation Vol 4 |magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |date=August 1998 |issue=34 |page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Sega_Saturn_Magazine_Issue_31_1998-05_EMAP_Images_GB#page/n31/mode/2up|title=Capcom Generation |magazine=[[Sega Saturn Magazine]] |date=May 1998 |issue=31 |page=33}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/Official_US_PlayStation_Magazine_Volume_2_Issue_8_1999-05_Ziff_Davis_US#page/n77/mode/2up/search/punisher |title=In the Year 2000 |magazine=[[Official U.S. PlayStation Magazine]] |date=May 1999 |volume=2 |issue=8 |page=78}}</ref> According to ''[[GamesTM]]'' in 2005, \"Capcom's ''The Punisher'' was a brutally violent fighter that perfectly captured the [[antihero]] it was based on. Featuring buckets of blood, some nasty moves and hordes of enemies, action came thick and fast, and so did the excitement.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/gamesTM023/GTM_023_eMag#page/n127/mode/2up/|title=It Started With a Fist |magazine=[[GamesTM]] |issue=23 |page=136}}</ref> The magazine too expressed a wish for it to be included in a compilation re-release for a more modern gaming system, in this case the [[PlayStation Portable]], but noted that the chances of this are slim due to a long-expired license.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://archive.org/stream/gamesTM044/GTM_044_eMag#page/n137/mode/2up/ |title=Compilation Heaven |magazine=[[GamesTM]] |issue=44 |page=138}}</ref>\n\n''[[Retro Gamer]]'' called it \"a forgotten gem in Capcom's back catalogue\" that \"is bursting with character and is extremely enjoyable,\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=McFerran |first=Damien |title=The Making Of... Dungeons & Dragons - Best Brawlers: Punisher (1993)\" |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=72 |p=52 |date=2010 |issn=1742-3155}}</ref> surmising the game did not sell well because the market was already flooded with beat 'em up games.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Buchanan |first=Adam |title=The Collector's Guide: Sega Mega Drive - Top Rarest PAL Games: The Punisher |magazine=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=112 |p=76 |date=2013 |issn=1742-3155}}</ref> Some media outlets also singled out for a special praise the game's particular elements, such as with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' regarding its arcade cabinet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/06/all-hail-the-90s-10-marvel-cabinets-that-ruled-the-arcades/the-punisher |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072809/http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2014/06/all-hail-the-90s-10-marvel-cabinets-that-ruled-the-arcades/the-punisher |archivedate=4 March 2016|title=The Punisher - All Hail the '90s: 10 Marvel Cabinets That Ruled the Arcades - Complex|author=Rich Knight|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> and [[Cracked.com]] regarding its [[game over]] sequence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_21313_the-5-most-sadistic-game-over-scenes-in-video-game-history.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150508211630/http://www.cracked.com/article_21313_the-5-most-sadistic-game-over-scenes-in-video-game-history.html|archivedate=8 May 2015|title=The 5 Most Sadistic 'Game Over' Scenes in Video Game History|work=[[Cracked.com]]|accessdate=23 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Crunchyroll]]'s [[Patrick Macias]] wrote: \"I'll confess my heart skipped a beat when I read ''The Punisher'' arcade game, the legacy of a misspent youth and countless tokens whittled away at [[Chuck E. Cheese's|Chuck E. Cheese]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/07/10/marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works-book-to-debut-at-san-diego-comic-con |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130120011727/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/07/10/marvel-vs-capcom-official-complete-works-book-to-debut-at-san-diego-comic-con |archivedate=20 January 2013 |title=\"Marvel vs. Capcom: Official Complete Works\" Book to Debut at San Diego Comic-Con |work=[[Crunchyroll]] |date=11 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Patrick Macias |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSome critics regard ''The Punisher'' as among the best of the beat 'em up genre, as well as among the best video game adaptations of comic books, especially of Marvel titles. In 2010, it was ranked as the tenth top greatest [[superhero]] game by [[IGN]]'s News & Features Team,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://ign.com/articles/2007/05/16/top-10-tuesdays-greatest-superhero-games |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170222120603/http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/05/16/top-10-tuesdays-greatest-superhero-games |archivedate=22 February 2017 |title=Top 10 Tuesdays: Greatest Superhero Games |work=[[IGN]] |date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=News & Features Team |url-status=dead }}</ref> and as the fifth top Marvel arcade game by [[iFanboy]]'s Josh Richardson.<ref name=if>{{cite web|url=http://ifanboy.com/articles/top-five-marvel-arcade-games/ |title=Top Five Marvel Arcade Games |work=[[IFanboy]] |date=6 March 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2014|first=Josh |last=Richardson}}</ref> [[Nerdist Industries]] included it among the top ten most iconic Marvel video games in 2013, calling it \"one of the few games that benefits from its cheesiness\" and stating that in 1993 the two-player experience \"was pretty much what ''[[Army of Two]]'' wishes it was today.\"<ref name=nerd>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/top-ten-most-iconic-marvel-video-games/comment-page-1/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193128/http://nerdist.com/top-ten-most-iconic-marvel-video-games/comment-page-1/ |archivedate=4 March 2016 |title=Top Ten Most Iconic Marvel Video Games \u00ab Nerdist |work=[[Nerdist Industries]] |date=8 November 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> That same year, it was also listed as one of top beat 'em up games of all time by [[Heavy.com]]'s Elton Jones,<ref name=heavy>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/games/2013/05/the-top-25-beat-em-up-video-games-part-2/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140917081157/http://heavy.com/games/2013/05/the-top-25-beat-em-up-video-games-part-2/ |archivedate=17 September 2014 |title=The Top 25 Beat 'Em Up Video Games Part 2 |work=[[Heavy.com]] |accessdate=17 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as being included amongst the best looking beat 'em up games from the [[16-bit]] era by [[Kotaku]] Australia's Gergo Vas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2013/03/the-best-looking-beat-em-up-games-from-the-16-bit-era/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130616074120/http://www.kotaku.com.au/2013/03/the-best-looking-beat-em-up-games-from-the-16-bit-era/ |archivedate=16 June 2013 |title=The Best Looking Beat em Up Games From The 16-Bit Era &#124; Kotaku Australia |work=[[Kotaku]] |date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Gergo Vas |url-status=dead }}</ref> David Hawkins of WhatCulture! declared it number one best comics-based arcade game in a 2011 ranking, being \"above and beyond all other arcade adaptations of comic books and their heroes,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/the-top-ten-comic-book-arcade-games.php |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131015192046/http://whatculture.com/gaming/the-top-ten-comic-book-arcade-games.php |archivedate=15 October 2013 |url-status=dead |title=10 Top Comic Book Arcade Games |work=WhatCulture |date=4 September 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=David Hawkins }}</ref> and Jon Ledford of Arcade Sushi opined that \"in terms of pure enjoyment, ingenuity, control, and graphics, ''The Punisher'' is the Best Retro Beat 'Em Up of all time.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arcadesushi.com/best-retro-beat-em-ups/ |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130927135033/http://arcadesushi.com/best-retro-beat-em-ups/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |title=10 Best Retro Beat Em Ups |work=Arcade Sushi |date=30 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2014 |author=Jon Ledford |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n