{"title_page": "The Corporation (record production team)", "text_new": "'''The Corporation''' was a group of [[songwriter]]s and [[record producer]]s assembled in 1969 by [[Motown]] label head [[Berry Gordy]] to create hit records for the label's new act, [[The Jackson 5]].<ref name='Gordy-Motown'>{{cite book |last1=Gordy  |first1=Berry |title=To Be Loved: The Music, The Magic, The Memories of Motown |edition=First |year=1994 |publisher=Headline Book Publishing |location=New York |isbn=0-7472-1417-4 |pages=415\u2013416 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&lpg=PA297&ots=JbtTtoUb1s&dq=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&hl=fr&pg=PA297#v=onepage&q=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|last=Larkin|first=Colin|date=2011-05-27|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=9780857125958|language=en}}</ref> They were the worst except michael\n\n==History==\nThe four members of The Corporation - [[Berry Gordy]], [[Mizell Brothers|Alphonso Mizell]], [[Freddie Perren]] and [[Deke Richards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deke-richards-motown-songsmith-dead-at-68-20130326|title=Deke Richards, Motown Songsmith, Dead at 68|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-05-29}}</ref> - were responsible for the writing, production and arranging of [[The Jackson 5]] number-one hit singles \"[[I Want You Back]]\" ([[1969 in music|1969]]), \"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]]\", \"[[The Love You Save]]\" (both in [[1970 in music|1970]]); as well as for other Jackson 5 singles such as \"[[Mama's Pearl]]\" and \"[[Maybe Tomorrow (The Jackson 5 song)|Maybe Tomorrow]]\" (both in [[1971 in music|1971]]).<ref name='Gordy-Motown'/>  They were also responsible for writing and producing \"[[Bless You (Martha and the Vandellas song)|Bless You]]\", the last hit by the trio [[Martha and the Vandellas]] before disbanding in 1972.\n\nLike Motown's previous production team, [[The Clan (composers)|The Clan]], which was pulled together to create the singles \"[[Love Child (song)|Love Child]]\" and \"[[I'm Livin' in Shame]]\" for [[The Supremes|Diana Ross and the Supremes]], The Corporation was intended as a replacement of sorts for [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]], who had left the label in late 1967 to start [[Invictus Records]] and [[Hot Wax Records]]. Occasionally, they were joined by Perren's wife Christine Yarian.\n\nGordy created The Corporation because he did not want any more \"back room superstars\", which the H-D-H team had become. The group members were never billed individually on the original Jackson 5 releases they worked on; even the songwriters' credit was listed as \"The Corporation\u2122\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/03/26/175376293/deke-richards-motown-producer-and-songwriter-dies|title=Deke Richards, Motown Producer And Songwriter, Dies|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Corporation disbanded in 1972, after [[Hal Davis]] had assumed creative control of the Jackson 5's output. After its disbanding, Motown would credit Gordy, Mizell, Richards, and Perren individually on compilation releases containing Corporation-created Jackson 5 material.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-corporation-mn0001344074|title=The Corporation {{!}} Biography & History {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2017-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JRHnCMUVb8C&lpg=PA87&ots=qTbXClItro&dq=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&hl=fr&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&f=false|title=Motown: The Golden Years: More than 100 rare photographs|last=Dahl|first=Bill|date=2011-02-28|publisher=Krause Publications|isbn=1440227837|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/michael-jackson/5651468/Michael-Jackson-and-Motown-the-man-behind-the-marketing.html|title=Michael Jackson and Motown: the boy behind the marketing|last=Brown|first=By Helen|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n;''Gordy, Mizell, Perren, Richards''\n*\"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]]\"\n*\"[[Bless You (Martha and the Vandellas song)|Bless You]]\"\n*\"Coming Home\"\n*\"Don't Let Your Baby Catch You\"\n*\"Goin' Back to Indiana\"\n*\"I Found That Girl\"\n*\"[[I Want You Back]]\"\n*\"I Will Find a Way\"\n*\"If I Have to Move a Mountain\"\n*\"I'm Gonna Get You\"\n*\"I'm So Happy\"\n*\"It's Great to Be Here\"\n*\"It's So Easy\"\n*\"Live It Up\"\n*\"[[The Love You Save]]\"\n*\"[[Mama's Pearl]]\"\n*\"[[Maybe Tomorrow (The Jackson 5 song)|Maybe Tomorrow]]\"\n*\"My Little Baby\"\n*\"Nobody\"\n*\"One More Chance\"\n*\"Petals\"\n*\"She's Good\"\n*\"[[Sugar Daddy (The Jackson 5 song)|Sugar Daddy]]\"\n*\"To Know\"\n*\"We've Got a Good Thing Going\"\n*\"You Made Me What I Am\"\n*\"Your Love Makes It All Worthwhile\"\n*\"You're The Only One\"\n{{col-3}}\n;''Gordy, Mizell, Perren, Richards, Yarian''\n*\"Do I Owe\"\n*\"[[Give Love on Christmas Day]]\"\n*\"In My Dreams\"\n*\"Is It Him or Me\"\n*\"Love Don't Want to Leave\"\n*\"Love Song\"\n*\"One And The Same\"\n*\"Up on the Housetop\"\n*\"Walk on Don't Look Back\"\n*\"Wings of My Love\"\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corporation, The}}\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Motown artists]]\n[[Category:Record production teams]]\n[[Category:Songwriting teams]]\n\n\n{{US-R&B-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''The Corporation''' was a group of [[songwriter]]s and [[record producer]]s assembled in 1969 by [[Motown]] label head [[Berry Gordy]] to create hit records for the label's new act, [[The Jackson 5]].<ref name='Gordy-Motown'>{{cite book |last1=Gordy  |first1=Berry |title=To Be Loved: The Music, The Magic, The Memories of Motown |edition=First |year=1994 |publisher=Headline Book Publishing |location=New York |isbn=0-7472-1417-4 |pages=415\u2013416 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&lpg=PA297&ots=JbtTtoUb1s&dq=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&hl=fr&pg=PA297#v=onepage&q=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|last=Larkin|first=Colin|date=2011-05-27|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=9780857125958|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe four members of The Corporation - [[Berry Gordy]], [[Mizell Brothers|Alphonso Mizell]], [[Freddie Perren]] and [[Deke Richards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deke-richards-motown-songsmith-dead-at-68-20130326|title=Deke Richards, Motown Songsmith, Dead at 68|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-05-29}}</ref> - were responsible for the writing, production and arranging of [[The Jackson 5]] number-one hit singles \"[[I Want You Back]]\" ([[1969 in music|1969]]), \"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]]\", \"[[The Love You Save]]\" (both in [[1970 in music|1970]]); as well as for other Jackson 5 singles such as \"[[Mama's Pearl]]\" and \"[[Maybe Tomorrow (The Jackson 5 song)|Maybe Tomorrow]]\" (both in [[1971 in music|1971]]).<ref name='Gordy-Motown'/>  They were also responsible for writing and producing \"[[Bless You (Martha and the Vandellas song)|Bless You]]\", the last hit by the trio [[Martha and the Vandellas]] before disbanding in 1972.\n\nLike Motown's previous production team, [[The Clan (composers)|The Clan]], which was pulled together to create the singles \"[[Love Child (song)|Love Child]]\" and \"[[I'm Livin' in Shame]]\" for [[The Supremes|Diana Ross and the Supremes]], The Corporation was intended as a replacement of sorts for [[Holland\u2013Dozier\u2013Holland]], who had left the label in late 1967 to start [[Invictus Records]] and [[Hot Wax Records]]. Occasionally, they were joined by Perren's wife Christine Yarian.\n\nGordy created The Corporation because he did not want any more \"back room superstars\", which the H-D-H team had become. The group members were never billed individually on the original Jackson 5 releases they worked on; even the songwriters' credit was listed as \"The Corporation\u2122\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/03/26/175376293/deke-richards-motown-producer-and-songwriter-dies|title=Deke Richards, Motown Producer And Songwriter, Dies|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Corporation disbanded in 1972, after [[Hal Davis]] had assumed creative control of the Jackson 5's output. After its disbanding, Motown would credit Gordy, Mizell, Richards, and Perren individually on compilation releases containing Corporation-created Jackson 5 material.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-corporation-mn0001344074|title=The Corporation {{!}} Biography & History {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2017-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JRHnCMUVb8C&lpg=PA87&ots=qTbXClItro&dq=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&hl=fr&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=%22the%20corporation%22%20motown&f=false|title=Motown: The Golden Years: More than 100 rare photographs|last=Dahl|first=Bill|date=2011-02-28|publisher=Krause Publications|isbn=1440227837|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/michael-jackson/5651468/Michael-Jackson-and-Motown-the-man-behind-the-marketing.html|title=Michael Jackson and Motown: the boy behind the marketing|last=Brown|first=By Helen|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n;''Gordy, Mizell, Perren, Richards''\n*\"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]]\"\n*\"[[Bless You (Martha and the Vandellas song)|Bless You]]\"\n*\"Coming Home\"\n*\"Don't Let Your Baby Catch You\"\n*\"Goin' Back to Indiana\"\n*\"I Found That Girl\"\n*\"[[I Want You Back]]\"\n*\"I Will Find a Way\"\n*\"If I Have to Move a Mountain\"\n*\"I'm Gonna Get You\"\n*\"I'm So Happy\"\n*\"It's Great to Be Here\"\n*\"It's So Easy\"\n*